{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"56698882-0b8d-464b-93b8-bc934facde7f","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's the rundown:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Lost test history in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed the **default test-ID generation strategy**. Every test gets a new ID, so ADO treats them as brand-new. To restore history, add a `.runsettings` file (or update your existing one) that forces the legacy scheme:\n\n```xml\n<RunSettings>\n  <MSTest>\n    <TestIdGenerationStrategy>Legacy</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n  </MSTest>\n</RunSettings>\n```\n\nThen reference it in your csproj or pipeline.\n\n---\n\n### 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a **class-level context** — it is not associated with any individual test. Accessing `TestName` (or `TestMethod`) now throws `InvalidOperationException`. This is by design.\n\nYour `SetupTests.cs` hits this directly on line 13:\n\n```csharp\nvar testName = context.TestName; // throws in v4\n```\n\n**Fix:** Remove or guard that call. If you need per-test setup, move the logic to `[TestInitialize]` instead:\n\n```csharp\n[TestInitialize]\npublic void TestInit()\n{\n    var testName = TestContext.TestName; // works here — instance-level context\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. Other v4 changes to watch for\n\n| Area | Change |\n|---|---|\n| **`[DataTestMethod]`** | Obsolete — use `[TestMethod]` with `[DataRow]` directly |\n| **`Assert.AreEqual(string, string)`** | Now uses **ordinal** comparison by default (was culture-aware) |\n| **`Assert.ThrowsException`** | Generic overloads are stricter about exact exception types |\n| **Cleanup timing** | `[ClassCleanup]` and `[AssemblyCleanup]` now run at end of class/assembly by default (was end of run) |\n| **Parallelism** | Parallel execution is enabled by default at the **method** level |\n| **`TestContext.Properties`** | Read-only in class/assembly init contexts |\n\nReview the [MSTest v4 migration guide](https://learn.microsoft.com/dotnet/core/testing/mstest-sdk-overview) for the full list. The parallelism change in particular can surface hidden shared-state bugs.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0e6dd669-1ef9-4856-995b-a270202baaa3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about MSTest v4 breaking changes. Let me address both issues based on my knowledge of MSTest v4 changes:\n\n1. **Tests appearing as new in Azure DevOps** - In MSTest v4, the default test ID generation strategy changed. MSTest v3 used a \"legacy\" ID scheme, but v4 defaults to a new stable ID scheme. This changes the test IDs, which means Azure DevOps sees them as entirely new tests, losing history.\n\n2. **TestContext.TestName in [ClassInitialize]** - In MSTest v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` methods no longer has a valid `TestName` property because class initialization runs before any specific test. Accessing `TestName` throws an `InvalidOperationException`. This is a deliberate change to make the API more correct.\n\n\nFor the test ID issue, they can restore the old behavior by setting `<TestIdGenerationStrategy>Legacy</TestIdGenerationStrategy>` in their .runsettings file. For the TestContext.TestName problem, they'll need to remove that call from ClassInitialize since there's no specific test context at that point. I should also mention a few other breaking changes like the unification of `[DataRow]` with `[TestMethod]` and some other attribute changes they might encounter.","outputTokens":1034,"requestId":"4C13:13B46:3B9260:456E73:6A0147A6"},"id":"e0be00ba-7ffe-4365-8606-532cfb00bae2","timestamp":"2026-05-11T03:06:36.023Z","parentId":"8968a67e-f962-4ff4-bd78-aec127de51cb"}
